      'en' => 
      array (
        'format' => 'html',
        'content' => 'The PHP Development Team announces the immediate availability of PHP 5.6.0. This new version comes with new features, some backward incompatible changes and many improvements.

**The main features of PHP 5.6.0 include:**

- [Constant scalar expressions](http://php.net/migration56.new-features#migration56.new-features.const-scalar-exprs).
- [Variadic functions](http://php.net/functions.arguments#functions.variable-arg-list) and argument unpacking using the `...` operator.
- [Exponentiation using the `**` operator](http://php.net/language.operators.arithmetic).
- [Function and constant importing](http://php.net/migration56.new-features#migration56.new-features.use) with the [use keyword](http://php.net/language.namespaces.importing).
- [phpdbg](http://phpdbg.com/docs) as an interactive integrated debugger SAPI.
- [php://input](http://php.net/wrappers#wrappers.php.input) is now reusable, and `$HTTP_RAW_POST_DATA` is deprecated.
- [GMP](http://php.net/book.gmp) objects now support operator overloading.
- File uploads larger than 2 gigabytes in size are now accepted.

For a full list of new features, you may read [the new features chapter of the migration guide](http://php.net/migration56.new-features).

**PHP 5.6.0 also introduces changes that affect compatibility:**

- Array keys won\'t be overwritten when defining an array as a property of a class via an array literal.
- [json_decode()](http://php.net/function.json-decode) is more strict in JSON syntax parsing.
- Stream wrappers now verify peer certificates and host names by default when using SSL/TLS.
- [GMP](http://php.net/book.gmp) resources are now objects.
- [Mcrypt](http://php.net/book.mcrypt) functions now require valid keys and IVs.

 For users upgrading from PHP 5.5, [a full migration guide](http://php.net/migration56) is available, detailing the changes between 5.5 and 5.6.0.',
